  "prompt": "Why does pubic and body hair stop growing after it reaches a certain length?",
  "response": "The growth of hair, including pubic and body hair, is regulated by a cycle that includes three main phases: the anagen (growth), catagen (transitional), and telogen (resting) phases. Each hair follicle operates independently and can be in a different phase at any given time.\n\n1. **Anagen Phase**: This is the active growth phase where hair cells divide rapidly. The length of the anagen phase varies for different types of hair. For body hair and pubic hair, this phase is relatively short compared to the anagen phase for scalp hair, which can last for several years. Because the anagen phase is shorter for body and pubic hair, they do not grow as long before they enter the next phases.\n\n2. **Catagen Phase**: This is a short transitional phase that lasts a few weeks. During this phase, the hair stops growing and begins to prepare for the telogen phase. The follicle shrinks and detaches from the hair shaft.\n\n3. **Telogen Phase**: This is the resting phase, which can last several months. Eventually, the hair is shed, and the follicle may begin a new anagen phase, starting the cycle over again.\n\nThe specific length that hair can grow before it stops is influenced by genetics and hormonal factors. Thus, pubic and body hair stops growing at a certain length because the anagen phase for these hair types is much shorter than for scalp hair, leading to shorter, more manageable hair lengths.",
